{
  "doc_id": "51893",
  "text": "Differential effects of sex and stress hormones on hippocampal and amygdalar function may also mediate sex differences in mechanisms of memory retrieval. In females, hippocampal estrogens regulate generalization of passive avoidance [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] , whereas in males, testosterone decreases amygdala activity during memory retrieval [CITATION_3] . Corticosterone alters hippocampus activation (Bohacek et al, 2015; [CITATION_4] , competition between memory systems [CITATION_5] , and is differentially increased during retrieval of fearassociated memories in males and females [CITATION_6] . Sex and stress hormones may thereby contribute to sex differences in retrieval-induced hippocampal and amygdalar mechanisms, and greater generalization of context fear in females.",
